</table>
<p><a id=3D"definition" name=3D"Definition"></a></p>
<h2>What is the Area of a Rhombus?</h2>
<p align=3D"justify">The area of a rhombus can be defined as the amount of =
space enclosed by a rhombus in a two-dimensional space. To recall, a rhombu=
s is a <a href=3D"https://byjus.com/maths/types-of-quadrilaterals/">type of=
 quadrilateral</a> projected on a two dimensional (2D) plane, having four s=
ides that are equal in length and are congruent.</p>
<p align=3D"justify">Read: <a href=3D"https://byjus.com/maths/what-is-mathe=
matics/">Mathematics for grade 10</a></p>
<p><a id=3D"formula" name=3D"Formula"></a></p>
<h2>Area of Rhombus Formula</h2>
<p>Different formulas to find the area of a rhombus are tabulated below:</p=
>
<table class=3D"table table-bordered">
<thead>
<tr>
<th colspan=3D"2">Formulas to Calculate Area of Rhombus</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Using Diagonals</td>
<td>A =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Using Base and Height</td>
<td>A =3D b =C3=97 h</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Using Trigonometry</td>
<td>A =3D b<sup>2</sup> =C3=97 Sin(a)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Where,</p>
<ul>
<li>d<sub>1 </sub>=3D length of diagonal 1</li>
<li>d<sub>2 </sub>=3D length of diagonal 2</li>
<li>b =3D length of any side</li>
<li>h =3D height of rhombus</li>
<li>a =3D measure of any interior angle</li>
</ul>
<p><img class=3D"aligncenter" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.com/wp-content/uplo=
ads/2020/08/Area-of-rhombus.png"><br>
<a id=3D"derivation" name=3D"Derivation"></a></p>
<h2>Derivation for Rhombus Area Formula</h2>
<p>Consider the following rhombus: ABCD</p>
<p><img title=3D"Area of a Rhombus Derivation" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.co=
m/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Area-of-Rhombus-2.png" alt=3D"Area of a Rhombu=
s Derivation"></p>
<p>Let O be the point of intersection of two diagonals AC and BD.</p>
<p>The area of the rhombus will be:</p>
<p>A =3D 4 =C3=97 area of =E2=88=86 AOB</p>
<p>=3D 4 =C3=97 (=C2=BD) =C3=97 AO =C3=97 OB sq. units</p>
<p>=3D 4 =C3=97 (=C2=BD) =C3=97 (=C2=BD) d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 (=C2=BD) d<su=
b>2</sub> sq. units</p>
<p>=3D 4 =C3=97 (1/8) d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub> square units</p>
<p>=3D =C2=BD =C3=97 d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub></p>
<p>Therefore, the&nbsp;<strong>Area of a Rhombus =3D A =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 d<=
sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub></strong></p>
<p>Where d<sub>1</sub> and d<sub>2</sub> are the diagonals of the rhombus.<=
/p>
<p><strong>Try This:</strong> <a href=3D"https://byjus.com/area-of-rhombus-=
calculator/">Area of Rhombus Calculator</a><br>
<a id=3D"how-to-calculate" name=3D"How to Calculate"></a></p>
<h2>How to Calculate Area of Rhombus?</h2>
<p>The methods to calculate the area of a <a href=3D"https://byjus.com/math=
s/rhombus/">rhombus</a> are explained below with examples. There exist thre=
e methods for calculating the area of a rhombus, they are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Method 1: Using Diagonals</li>
<li>Method 2: Using Base and Height</li>
<li>Method 3: Using Trigonometry (i.e., using side and angle)</li>
</ul>
<p><a id=3D"method-1" name=3D"Method 1"></a></p>
<h3>Area of Rhombus Using Diagonals: Method 1</h3>
<p>Consider a rhombus ABCD, having two diagonals, i.e. AC &amp; BD.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Find the length of diagonal 1, i.e. <strong>d<s=
ub>1</sub></strong>. It is the distance between A and C. The diagonals of a=
 rhombus are perpendicular to each other by making 4 right triangles when t=
hey intersect each other at the centre of the rhombus.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Find the length of diagonal 2, i.e. <strong>d<s=
ub>2</sub></strong> which is the distance between B and D.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Multiply both the diagonals, d<sub>1</sub>, and=
 d<sub>2</sub>.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4:</strong> Divide the result by 2.</p>
<p>The resultant will give the area of a rhombus ABCD.</p>
<p>Let us understand more through an example.</p>
<p><strong>Example 1</strong>: <strong>Calculate the area of a rhombus havi=
ng diagonals equal to 6 cm and 8 cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Given that,</p>
<p>Diagonal 1, d<sub>1</sub> =3D 6 cm</p>
<p>Diagonal 2, d<sub>2</sub> =3D 8 cm</p>
<p>Area of a rhombus, A =3D (d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub>) / 2</p>
<p>=3D (6 =C3=97 8) / 2</p>
<p>=3D 48 / 2</p>
<p>=3D 24 cm<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>Hence, the area of the rhombus is 24 cm<sup>2</sup>.<br>
<a id=3D"method-2" name=3D"Method 2"></a></p>
<h3>Area of Rhombus Using Base and Height: Method 2</h3>
<p><strong>Step 1: </strong>Find the base and the height of the rhombus. Th=
e base of the rhombus is one of its sides, and the height is the altitude w=
hich is the perpendicular distance from the chosen base to the opposite sid=
e.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Multiply the base and the calculated height.</p=
>
<p>Let us understand this through an example:</p>
<p><strong>Example 2:</strong> <strong>Calculate the area of a rhombus if i=
ts base is 10 cm and height is 7 cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Solution: </strong></p>
<p>Given,</p>
<p>Base, b =3D 10 cm</p>
<p>Height, h =3D 7 cm</p>
<p>Area, A =3D b =C3=97 h</p>
<p>=3D 10 =C3=97 7 cm<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>A =3D 70 cm<sup>2</sup><br>
<a id=3D"method-3" name=3D"Method 3"></a></p>
<h3>Area of Rhombus Using Trigonometry: Method 3</h3>
<p>This method is used to calculate the area of the rhombus when the side a=
nd one of its internal angles are given.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 1: </strong>Square the length of any of the sides.</li>
<li><strong>Step 2: </strong>Multiply it by Sine of one of the angles.</li>
</ul>
<p>Let us see how to find the area of a rhombus using the side and angle in=
 the below example.</p>
<p><strong>Example 3:</strong> <strong>Calculate the area of a rhombus if t=
he length of its side is 2 cm and one of its angles A is 30 degrees.</stron=
g></p>
<p><strong>Solution: </strong></p>
<p>Given,</p>
<p>Side =3D s =3D 2 cm</p>
<p>Angle A =3D 30 degrees</p>
<p>Square of side =3D 2 =C3=97 2 =3D 4</p>
<p>Area, A =3D s<sup>2</sup> =C3=97 sin (30<span style=3D"font-weight: 400;=
">=C2=B0</span>)</p>
<p>A =3D 4 =C3=97 1/2</p>
<p>A =3D 2 cm<sup>2</sup><br>
<a id=3D"solved-problem" name=3D"Solved Problem"></a></p>
<h3>Solved Problem on Area of Rhombus Formula</h3>
<p><strong>Question: Find the area of the rhombus having each side equal to=
 17 cm and one of its diagonals equal to 16 cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong> Solution:</strong></p>
<div id=3D"attachment_4952" style=3D"width: 408px" class=3D"wp-caption alig=
ncenter"><img aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-4952" loading=3D"lazy"=
 title=3D"Area of Rhombus Example Question" src=3D"https://cdn1.byjus.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2020/01/Area-of-Rhombus-3.png" alt=3D"Area of Rhombus Exa=
mple" width=3D"398" height=3D"232"><p id=3D"caption-attachment-4952" class=
=3D"wp-caption-text">Area of Rhombus Example Question</p></div>
<p>ABCD is a rhombus in which AB =3D BC =3D CD =3D DA =3D 17 cm</p>
<p>Diagonal BD =3D 16 cm (with O being the diagonal intersection point)</p>
<p>Therefore, BO =3D OD =3D 8 cm</p>
<p>In =E2=88=86 AOD,</p>
<p>AD<sup>2</sup> =3D AO<sup>2</sup> + OD<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>=E2=87=92 17<sup>2</sup> =3D AO<sup>2</sup> + 8<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>=E2=87=92 289 =3D AO<sup>2</sup> + 64</p>
<p>=E2=87=92 225 =3D AO<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>=E2=87=92 AO =3D 15 cm</p>
<p>Therefore, AC =3D 2 =C3=97 AO</p>
<p>=3D 2 =C3=97 15</p>
<p>=3D 30 cm</p>
<p>Now, the area of the rhombus</p>
<p>=3D =C2=BD =C3=97 d<sub>1</sub> =C3=97 d<sub>2</sub></p>
<p>=3D =C2=BD =C3=97 16 =C3=97 30</p>
<p>=3D 240 cm<sup>2</sup><br>
<a id=3D"practice-questions" name=3D"Practice Questions"></a></p>
<h3><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Practice Questions</span></h3>
